dead and millions more
displaced. And the

22:16.769 --> 22:21.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
role the United States has
played and will
play in the Middle East is now
being examined

22:21.907 --> 22:23.842 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in depth.

22:23.876 --> 22:28.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One group looking at these
issues is the Middle
East Strategy Task Force at the
Atlantic Council,

22:28.681 --> 22:31.050 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a think tank here in Washington.

22:31.083 --> 22:36.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Its co-chairs of the task force
join me now.
They are former Secretary of
State Madeleine

22:36.589 --> 22:42.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Albright, who served in the
Clinton administration,
and former National Security
Adviser Stephen

22:42.461 --> 22:46.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Hadley. He served in the George
W. Bush administration.

22:46.465 --> 22:49.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you back
to the "NewsHour."

22:49.535 --> 22:51.103 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Secretary Albright, let me start
with you.

22:51.136 --> 22:54.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Why take on this added
responsibility now
co-chairing this task force?

22:54.840 --> 22:56.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT, Former U.S.
Secretary
of State: Well, it's great to be
with you

22:56.342 --> 22:58.744 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and with my friend Steve.

22:58.777 --> 23:03.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reason that we did this is
because we're
concerned about the fact that
people are looking

23:03.749 --> 23:09.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the Middle East kind of in
short-term ways
and doing Band-Aids that have
been going on,

23:09.788 --> 23:14.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that it was really important
to take a
deeper, longer look, because the
issues, as

23:14.560 --> 23:18.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you raised them, are going to
take a long
time to resolve.

23:18.464 --> 23:24.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we needed to really take a
deeper look.
We also wanted it to be
bipartisan, and we

23:24.570 --> 23:30.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
looked at a number of areas. One
was the security
issue, but governance issues,
issues to do

23:30.709 --> 23:37.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with religion, refugees,
education, the economy.
We had papers that we did with
that.

23:37.182 --> 23:42.688 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then we went to the
countries in order
to really get a view of what is
going on.

23:42.721 --> 23:47.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We also have a lot of
international advisers,
but part of it, Judy, is -- and
the way that

23:47.059 --> 23:53.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you opened this, it is as
serious and terrible
as you described, but it also
has whole opportunities.

23:54.033 --> 23:55.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And those are the things that we
wanted to
look at.

23:55.901 --> 23:59.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that's what I
want to ask
you about, because you have just
come back,

23:59.672 --> 24:02.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as the secretary mentioned, from
a trip to
the region.

24:02.975 --> 24:06.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many people look at this part of
the world
and they see a crisis in every
country, whether

24:06.478 --> 24:15.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's ISIS, or a repressive
leader or a refugee
influx crisis. How do you see
the region?

24:15.788 --> 24:24.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you see it as a collection of
problems,
or a place that has a manageable
set of issues

24:24.363 --> 24:25.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you can get your arms
around?

24:25.964 --> 24:27.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY, Former U.S.
National Security
Adviser: Well, it's very tough.

24:27.766 --> 24:32.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it is a crisis in the
Middle East,
but it's also a crisis from the
Middle East.

24:32.838 --> 24:38.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I think people don't
realize is the
global consequences of this.
There are, of

24:38.177 --> 24:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
course, economic crises, but we
have, of course,
refugee flows that are taxing
neighboring

24:43.048 --> 24:47.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
states. They are a real problem
for the European
Union, putting enormous stress
on the European

24:47.619 --> 24:49.288 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Union.

24:49.321 --> 24:53.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is, of course, a terrorist
problem,
which is increased, as we saw,
with attacks

24:53.826 --> 24:58.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on Brussels and Paris. So it is
a crisis in
the Middle East. It is a crisis
from the Middle

24:58.864 --> 25:02.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
East. It's affecting the whole
country -- the
whole globe.

25:02.768 --> 25:07.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, as Madeleine
pointed out,
there are positive things going
on. One of

25:07.706 --> 25:13.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the things we noticed is, youth
are playing
a role in their societies. They
are empowered,

25:13.312 --> 25:16.615 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they are connected, they are
entrepreneurial.

25:16.648 --> 25:22.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you are seeing start-up
commercial ventures
starting. You are seeing
start-up bottom-up

25:22.388 --> 25:28.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
community organizations that are
trying to
solve local community problems.
There's a

25:28.394 --> 25:30.629 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
real bottom-up entrepreneurship
that is going.

25:30.662 --> 25:32.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But we don't hear
about that
here.

25:32.531 --> 25:34.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY: We don't hear
about them.

25:34.366 --> 25:36.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the things we have
tried to do
is -- one of the things we want
to do is sort

25:36.502 --> 25:41.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of bring that to the attention.
There is an
opportunity for the refugees not
just to be

25:41.640 --> 25:46.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a burden, but with the kind of
training and
education, they can actually be
a benefit

25:46.912 --> 25:52.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the societies in which they
are now residing
and to rebuilding the societies
they can return

25:52.251 --> 25:53.986 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to.

25:54.019 --> 25:57.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are opportunities for
education, to
teach people problem-solving and
to counter

25:57.890 --> 25:59.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the violent extremists.

25:59.725 --> 26:03.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you -- is
it possible,
Secretary Albright, to
prioritize which country

26:03.629 --> 26:07.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is more important than the
