the hope of a more prosperous
and secure Middle

27:33.952 --> 27:35.721 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
East.

27:35.754 --> 27:39.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in the short run, they're
vulnerable to
the terrorists. They're
vulnerable to the

27:39.358 --> 27:43.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tyrants. And in the short run,
we have to
deal with exactly the problems
you described.

27:43.762 --> 27:49.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the things we will do
is talk about
some of the things, that in the
short to medium

27:49.201 --> 27:51.136 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
term, we need to do.

27:51.169 --> 27:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to work on all three
problems together,
countering ISIS, bringing down
the sectarianism,

27:56.775 --> 27:58.544 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and solving the civil wars.

27:58.577 --> 28:02.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: I think one
of the things,
Judy, is that everybody is
concerned with

28:02.648 --> 28:07.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ISIS, or Da'esh, but the
priorities are a
little bit different, because
they also have

28:07.719 --> 28:09.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
internal priorities.

28:09.154 --> 28:10.122 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: They being?

28:10.155 --> 28:11.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: The
countries in the region.

28:11.957 --> 28:17.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, they have conflicts
between two
countries. For instance, the
Saudi-Iranian...

28:17.195 --> 28:19.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The historic...

28:19.097 --> 28:25.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: The historic
aspects,
or the Tunisians and Egyptians
are very worried

28:25.070 --> 28:26.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about the Libyans.

28:26.872 --> 28:31.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there is the general
aspect that dealing
with ISIS is a priority, but not
the only

28:31.944 --> 28:33.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
thing that they're thinking
about.

28:33.712 --> 28:36.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How does the
United States
avoid, Steve Hadley, being
overwhelmed by

28:37.015 --> 28:41.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this, because, as Secretary
Albright just
said, every country has its own
set of issues?

28:41.954 --> 28:47.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. has to look at this, it
seems, and
make some sense of it and figure
out what

28:47.593 --> 28:49.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
should be tackled first.

28:49.094 --> 28:51.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY: Well, it is an
overwhelming
problem.

28:51.430 --> 28:56.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the first point that we want
to make in
this task force is that the
United States

28:56.635 --> 29:01.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is affected by this problem, as
is Europe
and a lot of other countries.
And it is in

29:01.239 --> 29:06.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the United States' interest to
try to help
the Middle East get to a more
stable and prosperous

29:06.078 --> 29:07.980 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
future.

29:08.013 --> 29:12.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we heard in the region a lot
of criticism.
Some people said the United
States historically

29:12.684 --> 29:16.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and sometimes -- and the Bush
administration
did too much, and the Obama
administration

29:16.888 --> 29:20.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did too little. How come you
Americans can't
get it right?

29:20.092 --> 29:25.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the things we're
trying to do is
come up to and approach the
Middle East that

29:25.964 --> 29:31.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
protects our interests, that
contributes to
what the people in the Middle
East believe

29:31.570 --> 29:37.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is their future, but does it in
a way that
is sustainable over time?

29:37.409 --> 29:42.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, with the right
kinds of investments,
we can do that. But it is -- it
is -- we're

29:42.848 --> 29:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to have to rethink it.
We're going to
have to build a bipartisan
consensus. And

29:46.718 --> 29:50.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then we're going to have to
sustain it, because
this problem is going to be a
long time in

29:50.889 --> 29:52.624 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fixing.

29:52.658 --> 29:56.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it is not
easy to get it
right, is it, Secretary
Albright, in that,

29:56.194 --> 30:01.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as we just heard, sometimes, the
U.S. is seen
as doing too much, getting too
involved. Other

30:01.133 --> 30:04.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
times, it's seen as not doing
nearly enough.

30:04.069 --> 30:07.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: Well, I
think, because
it is so overwhelming and
complicated, we

30:07.939 --> 30:11.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need to do a better job of
explaining why
this matters to us.

30:11.543 --> 30:17.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Steve said, it's not only
things that are
happening inside, but also the
pressures from

30:17.949 --> 30:23.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- globally, and to try to
explain why it's
important to Americans. And it's
important

30:23.555 --> 30:30.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to us, obviously, because the
president wants
to keep Americans safe, but also
because we're

30:30.696 --> 30:36.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
concerned about the humanitarian
aspects of
it, obviously, the resource
aspect, our relationship

30:36.268 --> 30:37.969 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Israel.

30:38.003 --> 30:43.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we have to explain that,
but I do think,
also, we need to understand that
we found

30:43.442 --> 30:46.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's not easy to be the United
States there.
We were saying, damned if you
do, damned if

30:47.012 --> 30:51.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you don't. And we -- but I
believe, as so
does Steve, that we have to be
involved.

30:51.950 --> 30:57.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we are going to make a
point, I think,
of talking about what the
opportunities are,

30:57.189 --> 31:03.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
