wildlife corridors
that are scattered throughout
the valley.

42:46.264 --> 42:52.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But ensuring the protected areas
are connected
in perpetuity has been an
ongoing effort.

42:52.236 --> 42:58.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
About 25 percent of the land was
privately
owned when the plan went into
effect in 2008.

42:58.709 --> 43:04.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Landowners are not forced to
sell, but if
they do, they are compensated at
market rates,

43:04.382 --> 43:10.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or they can pursue minimal
development approved
by the plan. So far, tens of
millions of dollars

43:10.221 --> 43:16.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have been spent to secure about
90,000 acres,
or a third of the designated
conservation

43:16.194 --> 43:17.995 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
areas.

43:18.029 --> 43:23.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Still, many landowners,
developers, and even
some cities in the valley
initially opposed

43:23.901 --> 43:26.504 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the plan due to the limits on
development.

43:26.537 --> 43:29.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRETCHEN GUTIERREZ, CEO, Desert
Valley Builders
Association: There was some
struggles. Nothing

43:29.140 --> 43:32.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is ever easy when you take on a
project of
this size.

43:32.143 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: Gretchen Gutierrez is
CEO of the
Desert Valley Builders
Association.

43:36.681 --> 43:39.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRETCHEN GUTIERREZ: Right now,
what you're
seeing is the first phase, which
is models.

43:39.984 --> 43:45.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's going to be 166
single-family
houses, single and two stories,
in this development.

43:45.156 --> 43:50.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: The permitting process
here went
fairly quickly and no lawsuits
were filed.

43:50.228 --> 43:53.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why Gutierrez says
developers eventually
got on board.

43:53.564 --> 43:57.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GRETCHEN GUTIERREZ: What it's
provided for
our members is the surety that
they can move

43:57.602 --> 44:02.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their projects forward. I don't
think anyone
wants to see the plastification
of any of

44:03.007 --> 44:06.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the communities out here, or the
paving over
of the world with concrete.

44:06.444 --> 44:11.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same point in time,
you need to
have continued growth in terms
of new residences,

44:11.682 --> 44:15.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of new businesses, so
that it all
gives you a good quality of
life.

44:15.686 --> 44:20.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: Developers now pay a
fee for each
property they build, and that
money goes towards

44:20.491 --> 44:26.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
purchasing more land in the
conservation areas.
Additional funds come from a
variety of sources,

44:26.531 --> 44:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
including government grants.

44:28.966 --> 44:33.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While many in the valley agree
the plan is
working, whether it can hold up
over the long

44:33.638 --> 44:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
run is up for debate. Recently,
plans for
a new housing development within
this conservation

44:39.710 --> 44:45.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
area were submitted to the
county for consideration.
The project called Paradise
Valley would back

44:45.716 --> 44:50.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up to Joshua Tree National Park
on one side,
and the area is considered
critical habitat

44:51.022 --> 44:53.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for the threatened desert
tortoise.

44:53.591 --> 44:58.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The development highlights one
of the gray
areas of the plan: In the large
conservation

44:58.429 --> 45:04.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
areas, up to 10 percent of the
land can be
developed. The developer,
Glorious Land Company

45:04.569 --> 45:10.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Enterprises, declined to speak
with us on
camera, but provided a written
statement.

45:10.041 --> 45:15.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It reads in part that the
development will
incorporate new urbanism and
smart growth

45:15.479 --> 45:20.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
concepts, and that planners and
environmental
consultants for the project are
in consultation

45:20.318 --> 45:22.920 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with regulatory agencies.

45:22.954 --> 45:27.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cameron Barrows is one of a
number of scientists
and local environmental groups
opposed to

45:27.692 --> 45:29.493 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the development.

45:29.527 --> 45:33.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAMERON BARROWS: Without any
question, the
tortoise population will decline
if that happens.

45:33.431 --> 45:37.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's incumbent on all of us, the
scientists,
as well as everybody else that's
involved

45:37.301 --> 45:41.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this plan, to sit down with
these folks
on a regular basis and say,
remember why we're

45:41.405 --> 45:46.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doing this. Remember why you got
to do this
development or that development,
because the

45:46.811 --> 45:48.679 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
plan is here.

45:48.713 --> 45:53.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CAT WISE: The proposed
development still faces
extensive review before any
ground is broken,

45:53.084 --> 45:58.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but many here will be watching
closely for
how things play out as
conservation efforts

45:58.689 --> 46:00.124 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
continue.

46:00.157 --> 46:04.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Cat
Wise in Coachella
Valley, California.

46:04.161 --> 46:09.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Coachella
Valley's plan was
among the first of its kind when
it was developed,

46:10.001 --> 46:15.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, in recent years, the
strategy has been
catching on. There are now more
than 1,000

46:15.473 --> 46:19.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plans that seek to protect
single and multiple
species.

46:19.377 --> 46:24.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Efforts in the valley got a
boost when President
Obama named three national
monuments in Southern

46:24.749 --> 46:32.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
California, and one of them
overlaps with
the conservation plan.

46:32.890 --> 46:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight:
Imagine finding
a library from the 1940s, a
window into the

46:46.737 --> 46:53.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time before the deportation of
some 70,000
Jews from what was then
Czechoslovakia.

46:53.310 --> 46:57.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown reports on a
photographer who
learned something about himself
in the decades-old

46:57.982 --> 46:59.717 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bookshelves.

46:59.750 --> 47:04.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: At first glance,
you might
wonder: What is this? What am I
looking at?

47:04.889 --> 47:10.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then it hits you: These are
books, fragments
of books, in various states of
decay.

47:10.961 --> 47:16.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They were photographed where
they'd been left,
an abandoned schoolhouse in the
town of Bardejov,

47:16.567 --> 47:18.369 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Slovakia.

47:18.402 --> 47:24.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yuri Dojc, a successful art and
commercial
photographer who's lived in
Canada since 1968,

47:24.642 --> 47:29.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
returned to his native country
after his father's
death, to learn more about his
own Jewish

47:29.280 --> 47:31.282 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
roots.

47:31.315 --> 47:36.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He came upon the schoolhouse
almost by accident,
when a man he'd met told Dojc
there was something

47:36.654 --> 47:38.456 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
he must see.

47:38.489 --> 47:42.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
YURI DOJC, Commercial
Photographer: And then
he take us across the square. He
opened this

47:42.059 --> 47:45.896 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
door. And we were just stunned.

47:45.930 --> 47:48.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You had no idea
what you were
walking into?

47:48.299 --> 47:52.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YURI DOJC: I had no clue. But I
was stunned
by the beauty of decaying books.
I wasn't

47:52.603 --> 47:58.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thinking about history at that
moment. It's
the visual effect of these old
books was so

47:58.342 --> 48:00.111 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
beautiful.

48:00.144 --> 48:03.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Beautiful, but
horrible at
the same time, as the sense of
history set

48:03.881 --> 48:09.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in, for this was a Jewish
schoolhouse, left
as it had been in 1942, as Jews
were being

48:09.820 --> 48:16.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rounded up and taken by train to
the concentration
camp at Auschwitz.

48:16.460 --> 48:24.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The story is told in a
documentary Dojc worked
on with another emigre from the
former Czechoslovakia,

48:24.869 --> 48:26.704 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Katya Krausova.

48:26.737 --> 48:33.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The two began by seeking out and
listening
to the stories of Holocaust
survivors.

48:33.511 --> 48:39.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you went to meet these
people, essentially,
right? And one led to another.

48:39.416 --> 48:41.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATYA KRAUSOVA, Director, "Last
Folio": Yes,
exactly.

48:41.318 --> 48:47.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, here is a mixture and a
selection of some
that, by the time I joined him,
were dead,

48:47.758 --> 48:50.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and others that we had found
together, like
this couple.

48:50.594 --> 48:52.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. Tell me
about them.

48:52.363 --> 48:57.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATYA KRAUSOVA: They're very
important to
the whole story, because we
heard about them

48:57.268 --> 49:03.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in another town. And she didn't
want to even
let us come to the house.

49:03.340 --> 49:05.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, eventually I said, "Can we
just come
and have tea?"

49:05.743 --> 49:12.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once we were there, she
said: "I might
as well tell you my story. Maybe
nobody will

49:12.283 --> 49:14.218 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ever come again to ask."

49:14.251 --> 49:20.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so she told us her story, a
very strong
woman who talked about how they
were betrayed

49:20.191 --> 49:25.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and how, when they were taken to
the camps,
they actually believed that they
were going

49:25.663 --> 49:27.464 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to work.

49:27.498 --> 49:32.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she said that: "None of us
realized once
we got out of the truck that we
would never

49:32.136 --> 49:34.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be able to say goodbye to
anybody again."

49:34.705 --> 49:40.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Almost all of
these people
are now gone. In "Last Folio,"
the two try

49:40.811 --> 49:43.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to capture what remains.

49:43.414 --> 49:46.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So these are books literally
sitting on the
shelves as you walked in?

49:46.217 --> 49:48.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YURI DOJC: Yes, but I focus on
this particular
group.

49:48.352 --> 49:50.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why?

49:50.154 --> 49:54.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YURI DOJC: There is something
like a rhythm
here. There's colors, a chance
this color

49:54.792 --> 49:59.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to this color to this. So
there's a beautiful
-- look at this. The shades of
color, they

49:59.597 --> 50:01.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are just stunning.

50:01.332 --> 50:06.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: First an
aesthetic experience,
and then more, the books
standing in for,

50:06.103 --> 50:09.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
almost becoming, the lives of
the people who'd
held them in their hands.

50:09.874 --> 50:13.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YURI DOJC: I changed as a
photographer on
this project.

50:13.077 --> 50:19.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I only started understanding
what it's all
about. Until then, I was just --
I had fun.

50:19.950 --> 50:25.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I understand certain aesthetics.
But I was
missing something. And I
realized that you

50:25.856 --> 50:28.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
don't take art pictures with
your eyes. You
take them with your brains, and
I didn't know

50:28.926 --> 50:30.294 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

50:30.327 --> 50:32.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What does that
mean, to take
it with your brain?

50:32.496 --> 50:39.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YURI DOJC: You try to express
something which
was -- which is more than just
what I see.

50:39.236 --> 50:45.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a process of showing you
what happened
to those people. Like, I'm
projecting really

50:45.876 --> 50:50.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people and this whole pain and
all that is
lost into the pictures.

50:50.214 --> 50:55.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And there was one
more shock
for Dojc and Krausova when they
visited another

50:55.686 --> 51:00.324 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
abandoned building that
contained books from
all over Eastern Europe,
including, incredibly,

51:00.357 --> 51:04.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one that had belonged to Dojc's
grandfather,
who died at Auschwitz.

51:04.762 --> 51:12.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YURI DOJC: That was a miracle,
just pure,
pure miracle. And then I was
thinking if this

51:12.102 --> 51:13.804 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
whole journey's not a miracle.

51:13.837 --> 51:17.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATYA KRAUSOVA: So, nothing new
under the
sun, but very important to be
outraged.

51:17.841 --> 51:22.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: For Katya
Krausova, there's
more: important echoes to the
destruction

51:22.446 --> 51:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of people and culture still
going on today.

51:25.182 --> 51:31.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATYA KRAUSOVA: You know, what
is happening
right now in the Middle East is
very tragic,

51:31.789 --> 51:36.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because libraries are being
burned, and monuments
are being destroyed.

51:37.027 --> 51:44.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is our heritage, and we
need to somehow
do everything to preserve it.
So, when I say

51:44.535 --> 51:50.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
privileged to have worked on
this, it was
a privilege to learn people's
lives and their

51:50.574 --> 51:56.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stories. And I think we need to
go on telling
it to each other and to others.

